anifest in the moral and ethical understandings that embed individuals in specific communities. Vividly describing the moral dilemmas experienced in contemporary Chinese society, the rituals of happiness performed in modern weddings, the practices of conviviality carried out in shared meals, the professional tensions confronted by social workers, and the hopes and frustrations shared by political reformers, the contributors to this important study illuminate the causes of anxiety and reasons for hope in China today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAnxietyxSocial aspectszChina. 0aHappinessxSocial aspectszChina. 0aHappinesszChina. 0aStress (Psychology)xSocial aspectszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  acontemporary chinese society.  adifferent dimensions of happiness.  ahopes and frustrations of political reformers.  ailluminates causes of anxiety.  amodern weddings.  apractices of conviviality.  aprofessional tensions of social workers.  areasons for hope in china.  arituals of happiness.  ashared meals.  astudy of happiness in china.  avivid.1 aChen, Chih-Jou Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Lang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Deborah S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrer, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsu, Becky Yang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsu, Becky Yang, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMadsen, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadsen, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBO